                    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">The Wireless Power Consortium released the Qi2.2 specification in early 2026, delivering the most significant power upgrade since the original Qi2 launch. For OEM buyers and brand owners, this update reshapes product planning for H2 2026 and beyond.</p>

                    <div class="bg-green-600 rounded-2xl p-8 text-white mb-6">
                        <h4 class="font-black uppercase mb-4">Qi2.2 Core Upgrades</h4>
                        <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm">
                            <li><strong>25W Maximum Power</strong> — up from 15W in Qi2.0, a 67% increase in charging speed</li>
                            <li><strong>Tighter Magnetic Tolerances</strong> — alignment accuracy improved to +/-0.5mm, reducing energy loss</li>
                            <li><strong>Advanced Thermal Management</strong> — new adaptive power curve keeps surface temperature below 35°C at sustained 25W</li>
                            <li><strong>Enhanced FOD v2</strong> — faster foreign object detection response (under 200ms)</li>
                            <li><strong>Full Backward Compatibility</strong> — Qi2.2 chargers work with all Qi2.0 and legacy Qi devices</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-6 mb-6">
                        <h4 class="font-black text-brandBlue uppercase mb-3">What Qi2.2 Means for OEM Buyers</h4>
                        <div class="space-y-4 text-sm text-slate-600">
                            <p><strong>New Chipset Requirements:</strong> Qi2.2's 25W profile requires updated power management ICs. NXP (MWCT2x series) and Infineon (WLC1x15 series) have released Qi2.2-ready chipsets. Existing Qi2.0 chipsets cannot be firmware-upgraded to support 25W — a hardware redesign is necessary for the higher power tier.</p>
                            <p><strong>Backward Compatibility:</strong> Qi2.2 chargers automatically negotiate down to 15W for Qi2.0 devices and 5W for legacy Qi devices. No user intervention required. This means brands can launch a single SKU that serves the entire installed base.</p>
                            <p><strong>Certification Process:</strong> WPC updated its test procedures for Qi2.2. Products require additional thermal cycling tests (500 cycles at 25W) and tighter efficiency benchmarks (minimum 83% at 25W). Expect 6-8 weeks for full certification versus 4-6 weeks for Qi2.0.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>

